    "eyebrow": "Source Findings",
    "num": "03",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">03</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Source Findings</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Defining 'Texican': Historical Perspectives</h2><ul><li>'Texican' originally referred to Mexican residents of Texas</li><li>Term used during early 19th century before Texas independence</li><li>Distinct from 'Texian' (Anglo settlers) and later 'Texan'</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Historical sources indicate that 'Texican' described people of Mexican heritage living in Texas prior to and during early Anglo settlement, distinguishing them from Anglo settlers called 'Texians'. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A Mexican family living in Texas in 1825 would be considered Texicans, while Anglo settlers arriving under empresario contracts were Texians.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Identify which group a person belongs to if they were born in Texas of Mexican descent in 1820.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Confusing 'Texican' with 'Texian' or assuming all early Texans were Anglo settlers.</p></div></div>",
