    "eyebrow": "Source Findings",
    "num": "04",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">04</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Source Findings</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Origins of the Term 'Texican'</h2><ul><li>Derived from 'Tejano', Spanish for Texans of Mexican descent</li><li>Reflects cultural blending of Mexican and indigenous influences</li><li>Used in Mexican government documents and local usage</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">The term 'Texican' evolved from 'Tejano', highlighting the Mexican cultural heritage of early Texas residents. It was used in official and colloquial contexts to denote Mexican Texans. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Mexican land grant records from the 1820s refer to settlers as 'Texicans' or 'Tejanos', emphasizing their Mexican citizenship.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Explain how the term 'Texican' connects to Mexican identity in early Texas.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming 'Texican' is an English invention rather than rooted in Spanish language and culture.</p></div></div>",
