      "h": "Mexican Colonization Policies and Their Impact",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Understanding Texas as Mexican territory explains the origins of Texican identity and the arrival of Anglo settlers called Texians.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from lauriemooremoore.com; jinxschwartz.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Texas was part of Mexico until 1836</li><li>Mexican government encouraged settlement by Anglo empresarios</li><li>Texicans were established Mexican residents with cultural ties to Mexico</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Stephen F. Austin received a land grant from Mexico to settle Anglo families in Texas, creating a Texian community among Texicans.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Explain how Mexican policies shaped the demographic and cultural landscape of early Texas.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Ignoring Mexican sovereignty and its impact on early Texas settlement.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> lauriemooremoore.com; jinxschwartz.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup></p>"
