    "num": "07",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">07</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Concepts</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Cultural Identity of Texicans</h2><ul><li>Texicans blended Mexican, indigenous, and frontier influences</li><li>Maintained Spanish language, Catholic faith, and Mexican customs</li><li>Often bilingual and bicultural in interactions with Anglo settlers</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texican identity was multifaceted, reflecting a blend of cultural traditions and adaptation to frontier life. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A Texican family might celebrate Mexican religious festivals while engaging in trade with Anglo neighbors.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Describe how Texican culture differed from Anglo settler culture in early Texas.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming Texicans were culturally identical to Mexicans in central Mexico without frontier adaptations.</p></div></div>",
