    "eyebrow": "Cultural Identity",
    "num": "13",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">13</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Cultural Identity</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Texican Cultural Identity: Between Two Worlds</h2><ul><li>Texicans blended Mexican and Anglo-American cultural elements</li><li>Language, religion, and customs reflected this hybrid identity</li><li>Loyalty and self-identification were often fluid and situational</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texicans during 1820-1836 inhabited a cultural space influenced by both Mexican traditions and Anglo-American settlers. Their identity was not fixed but negotiated through daily life, language use, and political allegiance, reflecting complex loyalties. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s4\">[4]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A Texican family might celebrate Catholic holidays while speaking English at home and engaging in Anglo-style ranching practices.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Consider how living between two cultures might affect a person’s sense of belonging and political loyalty.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming Texicans were simply Mexican or Anglo ignores their unique blended cultural identity.</p></div></div>",
