    "eyebrow": "Cultural Affiliations",
    "num": "14",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">14</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Cultural Affiliations</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Language and Religion in Texican Communities</h2><ul><li>Spanish and English were both commonly spoken</li><li>Catholicism was the dominant religion, influencing social life</li><li>Religious practices blended Mexican traditions with local adaptations</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texican communities used both Spanish and English, reflecting their bicultural environment. Catholicism shaped social norms and community events, but local adaptations created unique Texican religious expressions. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s4\">[4]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Church services might be conducted in Spanish but include Anglo-American hymns or customs.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Identify how language and religion can serve as markers of cultural identity and community cohesion.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming all Texicans spoke only Spanish or were uniformly Catholic overlooks linguistic and religious diversity.</p></div></div>",
