      "secnum": "Deep Dive 14",
      "h": "Bilingualism and Religious Syncretism",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Texican communities used both Spanish and English, reflecting their bicultural environment. Catholicism shaped social norms and community events, but local adaptations created unique Texican religious expressions.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; everything-everywhere.com; en.wikipedia.org. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Spanish and English were both commonly spoken</li><li>Catholicism was the dominant religion, influencing social life</li><li>Religious practices blended Mexican traditions with local adaptations</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Church services might be conducted in Spanish but include Anglo-American hymns or customs.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Identify how language and religion can serve as markers of cultural identity and community cohesion.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming all Texicans spoke only Spanish or were uniformly Catholic overlooks linguistic and religious diversity.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; everything-everywhere.com; en.wikipedia.org <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s4\">[4]</sup></p>"
