    "num": "15",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">15</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Cultural Loyalties</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Texican Loyalties: Mexican Roots and Anglo Influences</h2><ul><li>Texicans often felt loyalty to Mexico’s government and laws</li><li>Anglo settlers introduced new political ideas and economic models</li><li>Loyalty could shift due to political pressures and personal interests</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texicans’ loyalties were complex, balancing allegiance to Mexican authorities with the influence of Anglo settlers advocating for different governance and economic systems. This duality shaped political tensions leading to the Texas Revolution. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A Texican landowner might support Mexican law but sympathize with Anglo calls for local self-government.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Analyze how conflicting loyalties might impact political decisions in a frontier society.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Viewing Texicans as uniformly loyal to Mexico or Anglo settlers ignores their nuanced positions.</p></div></div>",
