    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">17</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Settlement Patterns</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Geographic Distribution of Texican Settlements</h2><ul><li>Settlements concentrated along rivers and fertile lands</li><li>Land grants created clusters of Anglo-American settlers</li><li>Mexican towns and missions persisted alongside new settlements</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texican settlements were strategically located near water sources and arable land, reflecting economic needs and Mexican land policies. Anglo-American clusters coexisted with established Mexican communities. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Austin’s colony was centered along the Brazos River, facilitating agriculture and trade.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Analyze how geography influenced settlement success and cultural interactions.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Ignoring the persistence of Mexican towns and missions alongside Anglo settlements oversimplifies settlement patterns.</p></div></div>",
