      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> This checkpoint reviews key concepts about Texican cultural identity and settlement dynamics to reinforce understanding before advancing.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; lauriemooremoore.com; libguides.fau.edu; kwlibguides.lonestar.edu. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Texican identity blended Mexican and Anglo-American elements</li><li>Land grant policies shaped settlement patterns and legal obligations</li><li>Economic activities reflected hybrid cultural practices</li><li>Settlements faced geographic, cultural, and political challenges</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Recall how Austin’s colony exemplifies the intersection of Mexican policy and Anglo settlement.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Summarize how cultural identity and land policies influenced Texican communities.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Confusing Texican identity with purely Mexican or Anglo ignores their hybrid nature.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; lauriemooremoore.com; libguides.fau.edu; kwlibguides.lonestar.edu <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup></p>"
