    "eyebrow": "Texicans in Political Conflicts",
    "num": "25",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">25</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Texicans in Political Conflicts</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Texican Political Identity in Early Texas</h2><ul><li>Texicans were culturally Mexican but influenced by Anglo settlers</li><li>They played a key role in political tensions between Mexico and the US</li><li>Their loyalties were often divided during early conflicts</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texicans, as Mexican residents of Texas with Anglo influences, occupied a complex political position. Their identity shaped their involvement in disputes between Mexico and the United States, especially as tensions escalated before the Texas Revolution (s2, s7). <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s12\">[12]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Texicans often supported local autonomy but were wary of full independence, reflecting their mixed cultural and political loyalties.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Consider how Texican cultural identity might influence their political decisions during conflicts.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming all Texicans uniformly supported either Mexico or the US without nuance.</p></div></div>",
