    "eyebrow": "Interactions with Native Tribes",
    "num": "37",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">37</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Interactions with Native Tribes</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">The Caddo Tribe and Texican Relations</h2><ul><li>Caddo were a settled agricultural tribe in East Texas.</li><li>Texicans traded goods like horses and tools with the Caddo.</li><li>Relations included both cooperation and occasional conflict.</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">The Caddo tribe's agricultural lifestyle and established villages influenced Texican settlement patterns. Trade and occasional alliances helped shape early Texican economic and social life, though tensions sometimes arose over land and resources. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s14\">[14]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Texican settlers exchanged horses for Caddo crops, facilitating mutual dependence.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Consider how trade with the Caddo might have affected Texican settlement decisions.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming all Native American tribes uniformly opposed Texican settlers ignores complex relationships.</p></div></div>",
