    "eyebrow": "Interactions with Native Tribes",
    "num": "38",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">38</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Interactions with Native Tribes</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">The Comanche: Nomadic Power and Texican Conflict</h2><ul><li>Comanche were a dominant nomadic tribe in West Texas.</li><li>They controlled vast territories through skilled horseback warfare.</li><li>Texicans faced frequent raids and negotiated truces with Comanche leaders.</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">The Comanche's mobility and military prowess made them a formidable force. Texicans had to adapt by fortifying settlements and engaging in diplomacy to mitigate raids and maintain survival. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s14\">[14]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Texican ranches built fortified corrals to protect livestock from Comanche raids.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Analyze how Comanche dominance influenced Texican defensive strategies.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Overlooking the strategic diplomacy Texicans used with the Comanche reduces understanding of their survival tactics.</p></div></div>",
