    "num": "39",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">39</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Interactions with Native Tribes</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Negotiation and Conflict: Texicans and Native Tribes</h2><ul><li>Texicans engaged in both trade and violent conflict with Native tribes.</li><li>Negotiations often involved land use, trade rights, and peace treaties.</li><li>Conflicts arose from competition over resources and cultural misunderstandings.</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texican relations with Native tribes were multifaceted, involving diplomacy and warfare. Understanding these interactions requires examining specific negotiations and conflicts documented in primary sources. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s14\">[14]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A peace treaty negotiated between Texican leaders and Comanche chiefs temporarily halted raids.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Role-play a negotiation scenario between Texicans and a Native tribe considering competing interests.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming Native tribes were passive victims ignores their active role in shaping outcomes.</p></div></div>",
