    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">41</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Daily Life and Economy</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Texican Social Structure and Community Life</h2><ul><li>Texican communities were often centered around family and church.</li><li>Social hierarchy included landowners, laborers, and indigenous peoples.</li><li>Community events reinforced cultural identity and cohesion.</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texican social life was structured around family ties and religious institutions, with clear social roles. Primary letters and records provide insight into daily interactions and community organization. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s16\">[16]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A Texican town held regular church gatherings that served as social and cultural hubs.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Examine a letter describing a Texican community event and identify social roles involved.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming Texican society was homogenous overlooks social stratification and diversity.</p></div></div>",
