      "h": "Deep Dive: Using Primary Sources to Understand Texican Life",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Primary documents like letters and land grants offer direct evidence of Texican experiences, enabling reconstruction of their lifestyle and challenges.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from libguides.fau.edu; kwlibguides.lonestar.edu; guides.library.yale.edu; guides.lib.berkeley.edu. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Letters provide personal insights into Texican daily life and concerns.</li><li>Land records document settlement patterns and property ownership.</li><li>Analyzing these sources reveals economic and social realities.</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>A letter from a Texican settler describes crop failures and community support.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Analyze a sample letter to identify key themes about Texican life.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Overlooking context in primary sources can lead to misinterpretation.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> libguides.fau.edu; kwlibguides.lonestar.edu; guides.library.yale.edu; guides.lib.berkeley.edu <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s15\">[15]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s16\">[16]</sup></p>"
