      "h": "Deep Dive: Using Role Play to Explore Historical Negotiations",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Role play helps learners embody historical perspectives, deepening empathy and understanding of complex Texican-Native interactions.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from tshaonline.org; thestoryoftexas.com; libguides.tamusa.edu. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Simulate a negotiation between Texican settlers and Native tribe leaders.</li><li>Consider economic needs, land use, and cultural perspectives.</li><li>Aim to reach a mutually beneficial agreement or understand conflict causes.</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>One group represents Texicans seeking land access; another represents Comanche protecting territory.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Prepare arguments and negotiate terms reflecting historical realities.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Oversimplifying positions or ignoring cultural context reduces role play effectiveness.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> tshaonline.org; thestoryoftexas.com; libguides.tamusa.edu <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s14\">[14]</sup></p>"
