    "num": "52",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">52</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Primary Source Reliability</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Assessing Primary Sources on Texican Life</h2><ul><li>Primary sources include letters, land grants, official documents</li><li>They offer direct evidence but may reflect individual biases</li><li>Contextualizing sources is critical for accurate interpretation</li><li>Cross-checking with other primary and secondary sources strengthens conclusions</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Primary sources provide firsthand accounts but require careful analysis to understand their perspective, purpose, and limitations. They are invaluable for reconstructing Texican experiences. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s12\">[12]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A land grant document shows settlement patterns but may omit conflicts or social tensions experienced by Texicans.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Evaluate a primary source document for potential bias and context.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Taking primary sources at face value without considering author intent or historical context.</p></div></div>",
