    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">53</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Field Disagreements</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Contested Interpretations of Texican Identity</h2><ul><li>Historians debate whether 'Texican' implies ethnic or political identity</li><li>Disagreements exist on inclusion of Anglo settlers in 'Texian' identity</li><li>Some argue 'Texan' erases Mexican heritage, others see it as inclusive</li><li>Understanding these debates enriches historical analysis</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Scholars differ on how to interpret identity terms, reflecting broader questions about ethnicity, politics, and cultural assimilation in Texas history. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s17\">[17]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> One historian may argue 'Texian' was exclusively Anglo, while another includes Mexican-origin residents who supported independence.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Summarize two opposing views on the meaning of 'Texian' and discuss their implications.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Ignoring scholarly debates and presenting a single narrative as fact.</p></div></div>",
