    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">54</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Source Comparison</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Comparing Primary and Secondary Sources on Texicans</h2><ul><li>Primary sources offer direct evidence but limited scope</li><li>Secondary sources provide interpretation and context</li><li>Combining both types yields a fuller historical picture</li><li>Discrepancies between sources highlight areas for critical inquiry</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Analyzing both primary and secondary sources allows learners to understand raw historical data and scholarly interpretations, revealing complexities and contradictions in Texican history. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s1\">[1]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A primary letter describing a Texican's daily life may contrast with a secondary source's broader cultural analysis, prompting questions about representativeness.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Identify a point where primary and secondary sources on Texicans agree or differ and explain why.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Relying solely on one source type, missing context or nuance.</p></div></div>",
