    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">55</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Practice: Source Bias Identification</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Identifying Bias in Texican Historical Sources</h2><ul><li>Look for language that reveals author perspective</li><li>Consider the source's purpose and audience</li><li>Note what information is included or omitted</li><li>Assess how political or cultural context may influence content</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Recognizing bias helps learners critically evaluate sources, understanding that all historical documents reflect particular viewpoints and contexts. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s12\">[12]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s13\">[13]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A government document praising Texican settlers may downplay conflicts with Native Americans to promote settlement.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Review a provided excerpt and identify potential biases and their effects on the narrative.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming historical sources are objective and complete.</p></div></div>",
